//! Generated by clap-noun-verb-pack. Do not edit.
//!
//! SECOND proof, ALONGSIDE the `#[cfg(test)] mod
//! clap_noun_verb_routes_proof_tests` embedded at the bottom of
//! `src/clap_noun_verb_routes.rs` itself (never a replacement for it --
//! both are generated by every `ggen sync run`). This pack has no separate
//! hand-transcribed proof file the way `praxis-core-pack`/`star-toml-pack`
//! do: its Tier 1/2/3 proof lives inside the SAME template
//! (`clap_noun_verb_routes.rs.tmpl`) that also emits the routes, because
//! the wrapper fns and noun-registration fns it exercises are private to
//! that module -- a separate `tests/*.rs` integration-test crate has zero
//! visibility into them (see that template's own module doc for the
//! `linkme`/privacy details).
//!
//! That embedded Tier 2 ("drift canary") already renders its
//! `EXPECTED_COMMAND_COUNT`/`EXPECTED_DOCS`/`EXPECTED_NOUN_DESCRIPTIONS`
//! consts from the same `commands`/`nouns` SPARQL projection as the routes
//! above them -- so cap05 ("Generated verification") looks satisfied at
//! first glance: nothing is hand-typed. But it is the SAME gap
//! `refusal_taxonomy_sparql_derived_proof.rs.tmpl` and
//! `star_toml_config_sparql_derived_proof.rs.tmpl` close for their own
//! packs, just structured differently -- as ONE file instead of two:
//!
//! 1. Same render pass, not independently re-derived. Tier 2's consts and
//!    the routes/registrations they check are produced by the SAME Tera
//!    execution over the SAME query result, inside the SAME template. A
//!    field-mapping bug that corrupts one corrupts the other identically --
//!    Tier 2 can catch a routes/registration bug relative to *what this
//!    render pass computed*, but it structurally cannot catch the render
//!    pass itself having queried a stale or wrong `ontology.ttl`, because
//!    there is no second, differently-timed query to disagree with it.
//! 2. Frozen together, not asymmetrically fresh. `clap_noun_verb_routes.rs.tmpl`
//!    carries `skip_if: "ggen:local-override"`: once a consumer's checked-in
//!    file contains that marker, further syncs skip regenerating the WHOLE
//!    file -- routes AND the embedded Tier 2 proof together, in lockstep.
//!    If `ontology.ttl` changes after that point, the frozen file's own
//!    Tier 2 consts are frozen too, so they keep re-affirming the stale
//!    baseline instead of failing against the new ontology state. This
//!    template carries NO freeze marker of its own: its `LIVE_*` arrays
//!    below are re-baked from a live query against whatever `ontology.ttl`
//!    says at the moment THIS file is (re)generated, so it can distinguish
//!    "frozen and stale" from "frozen and still current" where the embedded
//!    proof cannot.
//!
//! This proof closes that gap by checking a DIFFERENT thing, not the same
//! thing more strictly: whether `src/clap_noun_verb_routes.rs` and
//! `docs/clap_noun_verb_routes.md`, as they actually sit on disk right now,
//! still agree with what `cnv:Command`/`cnv:Noun` individuals say RIGHT
//! NOW. It cannot and does not claim to validate "is the ontology itself
//! correct" -- only "has the checked-in generated artifact silently
//! drifted from the ontology since it was last written."
//!
//! ## Honest scope
//!
//! This compares rendered TEXT via substring search, not a parsed
//! Rust/Markdown AST -- the same limitation the embedded proof has. It does
//! not repeat the embedded proof's real handler-call (Tier 1) or real
//! `#[verb]`-macro CLI-dispatch (Tier 3) exercises -- duplicating those
//! here would be scope creep, not a second check; this proof's own scope is
//! artifact-vs-ontology text agreement only. `LIVE_STATIC_RESPONSES`'s
//! non-empty floor check is honestly scoped to today's ontology state:
//! `ontology.ttl` currently has exactly one `cnv:staticResponse`-bearing
//! command (`cnv:SessionPing`) -- if a future edit removed every such fact,
//! that specific assertion would need updating alongside it. It cannot
//! prove ggen's own SPARQL/Tera pipeline is bug-free in some absolute sense
//! -- only that, on the sync run that (re)generated this file, the live
//! ontology and the checked-in generated artifacts said the same thing.

const ROUTES: &str =
    include_str!(concat!(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"), "/src/clap_noun_verb_routes.rs"));
const DOCS_MD: &str =
    include_str!(concat!(env!("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR"), "/docs/clap_noun_verb_routes.md"));

